            "author_info": {
                "name": "Joshua Engel",
                "href": "/profile/Joshua-Engel"
            },
            "answer_text": "Confirmation bias is an inevitable result of the heuristics we use to get through daily life. Human beings innately seek out patterns in noise. There are always things contradicting even the most certain patterns; the system has to be robust despite them. Continually questioning every exception to the pattern would result in complete inability to act. It takes a learned response to avoid overuse of this heuristic when it comes to larger-scale patterns. Without consciously countervening it, you'll get confirmation bias by default. And it's good to apply that for large, slow, important things that we think of as \"conscious decisions\". But you're never going to be able to eliminate the natural tendency to confirmation bias because it's baked into how the brain thinks. ",
